### Scaling Distributed Ledgers and Privacy-Preserving Applications

**Findings:**
- **Availability & Fault Tolerance**: The system utilizes **sharding** to handle subsets of transactions, relying on intra-shard **Byzantine Fault Tolerance (BFT)** quorums where $n = 3f + 1$. For cross-shard operations, **Byzcuit** employs a **Transaction Manager (TM)** to coordinate communication, with a fallback mode ensuring liveness as long as at least one honest entity (e.g., an honest node or client) can take over the TM role. **FastPay** maintains availability by forgoing full consensus in favor of **Byzantine Consistent Broadcast**, allowing it to tolerate up to $f$ faulty authorities without performance degradation.
- **Performance Benchmarks**: **FastPay** demonstrated a peak throughput of **160,000 TPS** on 48 physical cores and sustained **80,000 TPS** with 20 authorities. It achieved intra-continental confirmation latency of **less than 100ms** (UK latency ~50ms) and inter-continental latency (US to Europe) of ~200ms. **Byzcuit** throughput scaled linearly to **~1,550 TPS** with 10 shards, maintaining client-perceived latency of **<1 second**. **Coconut** cryptographic primitives (verification) execute in ~10ms.
- **Safety & Soundness**: State coherence in **Chainspace** is managed through a **Hash-DAG structure**, where objects are immutable and identifiers are cryptographically derived from their creation history, preventing re-creation of inactive objects. To prevent **double-spending** in sharded environments, **Byzcuit** introduces **session identifiers** (transaction sequence numbers) and **"dummy objects"**. Dummy objects force output shards to participate in the first phase of the protocol, ensuring they witness the full transaction context and preventing replay attacks that exploit lack of context. **FastPay** ensures safety via "deliver once" semantics and commutative payment updates.
- **Compliance & Accountability**: The thesis details an **auditing framework** where shards periodically publish **signed hash chains of checkpoints** (Merkle trees) containing evidence of all committed or aborted transactions. It supports **partial audits** (proving specific transaction outcomes) and **full audits** (re-executing all transactions to verify state consistency), enabling the detection and tracing of malicious shards. **Coconut** provides a threshold issuance scheme for **selective disclosure credentials**, allowing for privacy-preserving identities and automated attribute verification. **ISO 20022** is cited as a standard for real-time domestic payments in the context of high-performance financial infrastructure.
- **Other Relevant NFR/Compliance Details**: **FastPay** is designed as a **Real-Time Gross Settlement (RTGS)** system that eliminates credit and counter-party risks of net settlement by settling pre-funded retail payments in real-time.
```

