title: "A Performance Analysis of BFT Consensus for Blockchains"
year: 2018
main_author: "J.D. Chan, Y.C. Tay, and Brian R.Z. Yen"
main_contribution: "Development of an analytical performance model using bottleneck and barrier analysis to optimize BFT consensus latency (HotStuff vs. IBFT) and determine optimal initial timer values ($τ_0$)."
evidence_type: "Research Article"
technical_constraints: "HotStuff scales linearly ($O(n)$) while IBFT scales quadratically ($O(n^2)$) regarding communication workload; performance is highly sensitive to the ratio of switch processing rate to validator processing rate ($r_s/r_v$)."
reference: "Chan, J. D., Tay, Y. C., & Yen, B. R. Z. (2018). A Performance Analysis of BFT Consensus for Blockchains. ACM."
doi: "https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.07622"
---

### A Performance Analysis of BFT Consensus for Blockchains

**Findings:**
- **Availability & Fault Tolerance**: The system maintains availability using **partial synchrony** assumptions and a **timer-based progress mechanism**. When a timer expires, it triggers an **exponential backoff** (doubling $τ_0$) and initiates a **full round change** or view change to elect a new leader. In **Istanbul BFT (IBFT)**, leadership is rotated, whereas in **HotStuff**, leaders are chosen randomly. The study specifically focuses on **crash fault resilience**, requiring a quorum of $2f + 1$ votes out of $n \ge 3f + 1$ total validators to proceed.
- **Performance Benchmarks**: The source cites several industry benchmarks: **Bitcoin** at 7 TPS with 60-minute latency, **VISA** at an average of 2,000 TPS (56,000 TPS peak), and the **Chain protocol** with 1-second consensus. In experimental simulations, **PBFT** implementations on commodity hardware reached **tens of thousands of TPS**. The researchers identified a "crossover point" where IBFT is faster than HotStuff for small numbers of validators ($n$), but HotStuff becomes superior as the network scales because IBFT's message complexity is **quadratic ($O(n^2)$)** while HotStuff's is **linear ($O(n)$)**.
- **Safety & Soundness**: State coherence is maintained by ensuring all validators add blocks to their local copy of the blockchain only after a **quorum of $2f + 1$ valid votes** is gathered. Safety (ensuring all copies are the same) is guaranteed as long as the number of faulty nodes does not exceed the bound $f$. The paper introduces a **barrier analysis** to model the exact moments nodes change phases, preventing data loss during network congestion by identifying whether the **validator (computation)** or the **switch (communication)** is the performance bottleneck.
- **Compliance & Accountability**: [Information not found regarding specific machine-readable standards like ISO 20022 or automated auditing protocols]. The source focuses on the **mathematical modeling of consensus latency** and **network topology impact** (Dragonfly vs. Folded-Clos) rather than regulatory compliance frameworks.
- **Other Relevant NFR/Compliance Details**: The research provides a specific formula for setting the **initial timer value ($τ_0$)** to minimize consensus time, recommending an allowance of **three standard deviations** above the expected consensus time to accommodate variance in message processing. It also demonstrates that competing network traffic can be effectively modeled by proportionally **reducing the switch processing rate ($r_s$)**.
```

