### Chainspace: A Sharded Smart Contracts Platform

**Findings:**
- **Availability & Fault Tolerance**: Chainspace maintains availability through **sharding** and **Byzantine Fault Tolerance (BFT)**, requiring a shard size of at least $3f + 1$ nodes to tolerate $f$ faulty members. It utilizes **S-BAC (Sharded Byzantine Atomic Commit)**, which composes BFT agreement (using the BFT-SMART library) with a distributed atomic commit protocol (2PC) to coordinate across shards. For node failure, it features a mechanism to recover from a malicious **BFT-Initiator** (leader); if an initiator suppresses transactions, other nodes in the shard can time out and assume the role, which is idempotent.
- **Performance Benchmarks**: On a testbed of 60 cores (15 shards), Chainspace achieved **350 TPS**. Throughput scales linearly with the number of shards, increasing by an average of **22 TPS for every shard added** (assuming 4 nodes per shard). **Client-perceived latency** was recorded at approximately **69ms** under moderate loads (20–60 TPS), rising to **210ms** as the system approached capacity. The source uses **Visa** (2,000 average / 56,000 peak TPS) as a primary benchmark for financial high-volume scenarios.
- **Safety & Soundness**: State coherence is enforced through a **Hash-DAG structure** where objects are immutable and identified by cryptographic hashes of the transactions that created them. **Double-spending** is prevented by the **S-BAC protocol**, which uses a **locking mechanism** during the "prepare" phase to ensure a shard only commits one transaction per active input object. Once committed, objects are marked **inactive**, and the system axiomatically ensures that no sequence of valid transactions can re-create an object with the same identifier.
- **Compliance & Accountability**: The platform provides **high auditability** through **signed hash chains of checkpoints** (Merkle trees) published by each shard. It supports **partial audits** (proving the fate of a specific transaction in $O(s + \log N)$ time) and **full audits** (re-executing the entire history to detect Byzantine behavior). Malicious shards are identified when their signed records are found to be "incompatible" with statements sent to other shards. Privacy-friendly compliance is achieved through **Zero-Knowledge Proofs (SNARKs)**, allowing checkers to verify transaction invariants without revealing secret data. [ISO 20022 was not explicitly mentioned].
- **Other Relevant NFR/Compliance Details**: Chainspace implements **CSCoin** as a system smart contract to manage accounting and prevent DoS attacks through transaction processing fees. The architecture supports **smart contract composition**, allowing higher-level contracts to rely on the validated traces of sub-calls.
```

