### Implicit Consensus: Blockchain with Unbounded Throughput

**Findings:**
- **Availability & Fault Tolerance**: The system maintains availability by decoupling transaction processing from global consensus. It utilizes an existing BFT scheme (e.g., PBFT) to reach agreement on **Check Points (CPs)**, which "seal" the state of individual blockchains,. To ensure liveness without a global termination requirement, it relies on a **self-interest phenomenon**: it is in the interest of the transacting parties (e.g., the issuer) to provide the necessary proofs to other nodes to ensure their transaction is validated,. The system is **censorship-free** because any node that has validated a transaction can independently provide the complete and correct proofs to any other honest node.
- **Performance Benchmarks**: The source claims **unbounded throughput** because the rate of valid transactions is independent of the global consensus scheme,. In optimal scenarios where nodes are paired and only transact with each other, throughput reaches **$O(CN)$**, where $C$ represents combined communication and computation capacity. In the worst case (all nodes transacting with all others), throughput is **$O(C)$**. Latency remains dependent on the underlying BFT algorithm used for CPs, but communication overhead for consensus is reduced to **$O(N)$**,.
- **Safety & Soundness**: State coherence is maintained through **Individual Blockchains** for each node, where transactions are only recorded by the related parties,. **Double-spending** is prevented by a local **Validation Scheme** that checks for forks (Definition 10) and ensures transaction sources have not been previously used,. Safety is guaranteed because CPs included in the global consensus make all prior transactions on that chain **tamper-proof**,. Correctness is maintained even in network partitions because honest nodes only validate transactions after collecting **complete and correct proofs** (entire chain segments back to the genesis block or initial balance),.
- **Compliance & Accountability**: Accountability is enforced through a **Public Key Infrastructure (PKI)** where every transaction must be signed by the sender's private key, ensuring non-repudiation,. The system facilitates automated auditing by keeping a permanent record of **invalid transactions**, which honest nodes can use to identify and take actions against malicious actors. To mitigate spam and DDoS attacks, the authors propose the use of **reputation or blacklist schemes**. [Machine-readable standards like ISO 20022 were not mentioned].
- **Other Relevant NFR/Compliance Details**: The system introduces **spontaneous sharding**, where rational nodes optimize storage and transmission costs by only validating and recording the specific "proofs" (transaction history and chain segments) relevant to their own transactions,.
```

