### Self-stabilizing Byzantine-tolerant Recycling

**Findings:**
- **Availability & Fault Tolerance**: The protocol maintains availability through **self-stabilization**, allowing the system to automatically recover from **arbitrary transient faults** (e.g., corruption of program counters, packet payloads, or sequence numbers) in addition to tolerating up to **$t < n/3$ Byzantine or crash process failures**. It utilizes a **synchronous recycling service** to manage **asynchronous consensus objects**, ensuring that resources used by completed invocations are released and made available for reuse. A key mechanism is the **simultaneous increment-or-get index (SGI-index)**, which ensures all non-faulty nodes agree on which object in a constant-size array is currently active.
- **Performance Benchmarks**: The system is designed to stabilize within **expected $O(\kappa)$ synchronous rounds**, where $\kappa$ is a predefined constant related to the number of Byzantine processes ($t$) and the log size. While specific TPS for the recycling mechanism itself is not the focus, it is designed to facilitate "communication-intensive" components like consensus objects which may use **$O(n^2)$ messages per invocation**. To optimize performance, a single recycling action can be performed for a **batch of $\delta$ objects**.
- **Safety & Soundness**: State coherence is maintained by requiring that a consensus object is only recycled after all non-faulty processes have retrieved the decided values, satisfying the **COR-agreement** property where all nodes simultaneously set an object's status to "unused". To prevent data loss or premature reuse (avoiding a "chicken-and-egg" problem), the system ensures that the **$(k+1)$-th invocation** can only start after the **$k$-th instance** has reached agreement on collective delivery. The **wasDelivered()** interface ensures that if one non-faulty node reports a delivery, all others will eventually do so, maintaining global state consistency.
- **Compliance & Accountability**: The framework enforces accountability by assuming **private channels** between nodes to prevent **spoofing or impersonation attacks**. It uses an **SSBFT multivalued consensus protocol** to decide on a single piece of evidence regarding recyclability from all collected nodes, acting as an automated auditing trigger for the recycling process. The mechanism relies on **random common coins (RCCs)** for unpredictable, randomized recovery strategies to guarantee agreement on the ledger index even after a system-wide state corruption. [ISO 20022 was not mentioned].
- **Other Relevant NFR/Compliance Details**: The solution employs a **sliding window technique** and a global restart mechanism once a maximum sequence number is reached to maintain memory constraints. It uses **communication piggybacking** to multiplex timed reliable communication (for recycling) and fair communication (for consensus objects).
```

